snippet.textDisplay:
Weta Workshop are amazing. I love all of their work. They have blown my mind time and again with their expertise. I am very much looking forward to seeing what they do for Avatar 2, 3, 4 ... and 5?

FYI - I had heard a rumour James was considering using Ocolus Rifts (or another VR headset) to have limited showings of the film in VR where you could turn your head and see people or things talking or moving behind you but also be able to look around and see the entire environment in 3D. I very much wish this rumour to be true but I can imagine the experience would be extremely expensive; and may not be for the actual movies.

snippet.textDisplay: Final Fantasy: Advent Children. The textures are so so so good, but the characters firmly live in Uncanny Valley City. Mouth movement, hair movement, all of it. Would love to hear your analysis on what worked and what didn’t work about the photorealism of that movie. And maybe some of the design decisions that go into adapting big-anime-eyed polygons into more realistic-looking, human-looking models.
snippet.textOriginal: Final Fantasy: Advent Children. The textures are so so so good, but the characters firmly live in Uncanny Valley City. Mouth movement, hair movement, all of it. Would love to hear your analysis on what worked and what didn’t work about the photorealism of that movie. And maybe some of the design decisions that go into adapting big-anime-eyed polygons into more realistic-looking, human-looking models.

snippet.textDisplay:
Soooo... while I know that it might have been rather rude to bring the subject up... how could you NOT ask about the origins of one of the worst VFX shots ever created while talking about King Kong?

I mean, obviously your guest Matt Aitken deserves a lot of respect for his work and for WETA's overall body of work... but Corridor Crew has bashed the dinosaur stampede shot and it has been universally held up as one of the worst CGI shots.

Did you get any inside information on what happened with that shot?
